nd the state, and the criteria for appointing individuals to academic positions. Edward Shils understood the university as a great symphonic conductor comprehends the value of each instrument and section, both separately and in cooperation. The Calling of Education offers Shils's insightful perspective on problems that are no less pressing than when he first confronted them. Edward Shils (1910-1995) was distinguished service professor in the Committee on Social Thought and the department of sociology at the University of Chicago. Among his many books published by the University of Chicago Press are Portraits: A Gallery of Intellectuals and the three-volume Selected Papers of Edward Shils.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aCollege teachersxProfessional ethics. 0aEducation, HigherxAims and objectives. 0aEducation, HigherxPhilosophy. 0aEducation, HigherxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aUniversities and collegeszUnited StatesxAdministration. 7aEDUCATION / General.2bisacsh1 aGrosby, Steven, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUChP eBook-Package Archive 1990-1999z978311066785140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226753409423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226753409.jpg  a978-3-11-066785-1  UChP eBook-Package Archive 1990-1999c1990d1999  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles